comments.text:
Sorry to disappoint, but de Laval nozzle is utterly useless for incompressible liquids. It is designed for gases (see Wiki) to obtain best speed/pressure ratio on the exit of the nozzle.
This looks cool, but it does not provide any benefit compare to simple cylindrical nozzle.

comments.text: Yup, Fogl is right. de Laval nozzles are for converting sonic isentropic flows to higher exit speeds (and thus thrust). Neither the (incompressible) water nor the compressed but relatively low speed air exiting the rocket are likely to get advantage from this.

title: Lulzbot Laser Upgrade in front of Extruder

description.text:
This is a new mount for placing the J Tech Photoincs laser upgrade kit in front of the extruder of the Lulzbot printers. This means you can print then laser with no changes. Full instruction for how to do this are at:
http://jtechphotonics.com/?page_id=2438 Some videos of the laser capabilities:
https://youtu.be/NV5NWtxTdn4
https://youtu.be/-DyqshA7Jn4

Full instruction with photos are at:
http://jtechphotonics.com/?page_id=2438 Here is the excerpt:
One of the newer open source printers that is gaining a popular reputation for being a well built printer that just plain works is the printers from Lulzbot. We got our Lulzbot mini about three months ago and it prints perfectly on every print running production every day non-stop! Needless to say, we love our Lulzbot, but it is missing something… A Laser! You can’t have a 3D printer without a laser! Come on now. Here we outline the instructions for upgrading the Lulzbot mini, but the Taz is just the same. It has the same extruder and electronics, the platform is just a bit larger. If you want to see how to build a laser only system, check out our blog post here. So here it is – Instructions on how to upgrade the Lulzbot printers. Let’s start! Electronics
We are going to use the fan1 connection on the Rambo board to control the laser. It has PWM control needed to do picture engraving and is easily controlled with M106/107 commands in software. We decided to mount the laser in front of the extruder so you can print then laser without any changes. We choose to mount the driver on the side of the printer because there was already a hole for the driver to attach to and the existing cables in the laser upgrade kit will reach it. We routed the laser and fan cables up the wiring harness chain to the Z axis and made it all nice and tidy with zip ties. You can cut the fan cable and either splice the wires to the laser driver intput H2 or maybe even put a nice little switch in to change between laser and printing. Mechanical
We designed a nice little mount for the laser to attach to in front of the extruder. The good news is it just needs one additional screw! Get a small M3 screw and it will mount to the existing little hole in the aluminum plate on the extruder mount. Take the other screw from the left of the assembly off and put it through the new mount. To protect the build plate we put some plastic with a sheet of aluminum on top of it and taped it in place. You can use whatever material you want for a sacrificial material and tape it or secure it somehow to the platform. Software
We had to modify the firmware of the Lulzbot because the PWM frequency was set way to high for it to control the laser. You can get the firmware from Lulzbot here: http://download.lulzbot.com/Mini/1.0/software/firmware/ or for the TAZ printer it is in the software folder here: http://download.lulzbot.com/TAZ/ You need to load all of the files into your Arduino compiler and make a new sketch that shows all of the files. Make sure you have the newest version of the compiler downloaded from Arduino HERE. Set you board as Arduino Mega or Mega 2560 . Then in config.h, comment out the line: //#define FAST_PWM_FAN Then make sure your are connected to the correct COM port and the printer is connected to the computer and compile the firmware. You are now done! We used Repetier Host to control the printer. We like the “preview” feature for the G Code and it does a good job with everything else as well. You need to adjust some of the settings because the table will be slightly smaller. Here are instructions for the configuration: http://jtechphotonics.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Lulzbot-Laser-Setup-Instructions.pdf Ok, now let’s get to the upgrading with pictures! Step 0 – Print out the mount The mount has been designed to sit right in front of the extruder assembly and also allow for the fan upgrade to be mounted as well. Step 1. Remove the left screw on the extruder assembly. Step 2 – Attach Laser to mount Step 3 – Prepare screws to attach to printer Step 4 – Place mount in front of extruder and screw in. Step 5 – Route cables to the back cable chain. Step 6 – Zip tie cables to chain. Step 7 – Put laser driver on front side of printer. Step 8 – Use existing hole to mount the laser driver. Step 9 – Change out the driver nuts to make spacer to hold driver when you screw it in. Step 10 – Open electronics to get to the fan cable. Step 11 – Cut fan 1 cable and splice in cable for laser driver. Step 12 – Open the Arduino SW and load the Marlin firmware (either Mini or Taz). In config.h, comment out the line FAST_PWM_FAN like in the picture. You can also use SW PWM, but make sure it is not above 5KHz. DONE! READY for LASER!!!

The term 'biomimetic' means something artificial that mimics nature. This 3D printed biomimetic craft mimics the flotation system of Gerridae, or the water strider. This bug floats on the surface of a body of water, using it's long, slender legs to take advantage of the surface tension on the water. Download, print, and share!
Watch the video here: https://goo.gl/c5VRcI
Also, watch this awesome video of natural water Striders: https://youtu.be/RphuMEUY3Og Version 2 -6/30/2015
Version 2 has added flotation due to the fact that I added "feet" to attach to the ends of the legs. These "feet" act like the miniscule hairs on natural strider's feet, enabling it to float on the surface tension. Be sure to print them and add them to your strider!

Print with a light infill, as surface tension is not very strong. After printing both pieces, stick the legs into the slots on the body (you may need to glue them). Next, use silicone to secure the floats (print X4) to the legs. Enjoy your strider boat! Settings: Legs:

description.text: He has been called many things from "a giant furry thing" to "a rabbit-like spirit". Basically, he is a spirit of the forest. Totoro is not a traditional Japanese character: he came completely from Miyazaki's imagination. However, he is obviously a mixture of several animals: tanukis (the Japanese version of raccoons), cats (the pointed ears and the facial expressions), and owls (the chevron markings on their chests and the "ooo"-ing sound they make with their ocarinas at night). The name "Totoro" comes from Mei mispronouncing (she has a tendency to do so, though it wasn't clear in the dub) the word "tororu", which is the Japanese word for "troll". When Satsuki asks her "Totoro? You mean, the Troll in our book?" she is referring to their book "Three Mountain Goats" (The Three Billy Goats Gruff). In the closing credits you can see their mother reading the book to them. Although it's hard to see it on the tape, in the picture book for the movie you can see the picture on the cover shows a goat running over a bridge while a Totoro-like troll looks up from underneath the bridge. (Source http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/totoro/faq.html)

title: HBP Heated build plate for the Makerbot Replicator 2 & 2X - Makes your Replicator a real tool!

description.text:
IDE heated glass build plate system for the MakerBot Replicator 2 & 2X Compatibility: The IDE HBP System is compatible with every MakerBot Replicator 2 and Replicator 2X. You have to do no modifications on your device. What are the benefits? If you have a Replicator 2, the IDE heated build plate system offers you the option to use all the 3D printing materials that are available, you are no longer limited to PLA. Even if you still want to use PLA only, the heated build plate makes it possible to print very large parts, with no warping and an absolute flat and smooth bottom surface. You can print directly onto the glass surface. So you need no tapes (saves you money and work) anymore and also get an absolute smooth bottom surface on your objects and can remove the parts from the plate after cooling down with ease. Our IDE heated build plate system has an absolute flat surface, so you have a perfect first layer even on large parts and less print failures. More comfort cause of the removable (magnetic) glass plate. No more constantly leveling the build plate - you can remove and replace the glass plate and print without leveling. Who will like to use it? We have professional users like Bosch,Volkswagen, Airbus and many other huge companies, as well as universities, schools, small businesses and private users. So in fact everyone with a MakerBot Replicator 2 or 2X will love the improvements that our upgrade brings. You will see quality improvements as well as more comfort and less maintenance. Is it complicated to install? Not at all! The installation is really as easy as playing lego, we ship it with a detailed, pictured assembly guide and really everyone can install it in just a few minutes. Its all "plug and print" (also see the video further down). What is part of the offer?
Completely preassembled build plate with integrated heater and temperature sensor. With wires and terminals. You really just have to plug it into the connectors that your Replicator has from stock.
With detailed assembly guide.
With 1 glass plate - if you need more than one, you can order it separately.
Time needed for the upgrade:
about 10 minutes, can be made by everyone without special skills. The set can be built out and downgraded to the original factory condition without problems. There is no manipulation on the original parts needed.
The upgrade built plate is compatible to the original Replicator 2 & 2X Z-axis as well as (for sure) with our aluminium Z-axis upgrade. 100% made in Germany Here you can see a "how to video" that a kind and satisfied customer made for us: https://youtu.be/VSIu8YKadmc You can order the kit over eBay:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/IDE-MakerBot-Replicator-2-2X-HBP-heated-glass-build-plate-bed-upgrade-/253042675192?epid=879494250&hash=item3aea84cdf8:g:hLIAAOSw0QFXBsfE or directly over the webshop http://www.ide-3d.de:
http://www.ide-3d.de/epages/83488941.sf/en_US/?ObjectPath=/Shops/83488941/Products/MKB2hbp

description.text:
The stock Ultimaker is a great 3d printer which uses PLA by default as the print material. I like it, but I like ABS much more. Without a heated bed it's nearly impossible to get good printing results when using ABS - a heat bed is a must. To get even better results with ABS it's a good idea to enclose the entire build area to get higher and stabilized temperatures. A heat chamber is not nessasry, but when you want to go big with your models then it truly helps getting good print results with ABS. My Ultimaker now features:
  • heated + illuminated build platform
  • heated + illuminated build chamber
  • permanent print plate for ABS and PLA
  • direct drive system
  • active cooled stepper motors
  • dual-fan setups for hot-end, UM pcb, and second psu
  • modified H3 extruder
  • capability to load big 2.2 kg spools
  • hardware switches for hot-end, heat bed, cooling and light
  • UltiController
  • slightly improved build room (over 200 cmÂ³ more build space)
    and more...
    • This project is finished, but I still see some room for improvements, e. g. a dualstrusion setup. Maybe also some PAINT for the wood panels. :-) Also some minor improvements I'll install in the next few weeks. Almost all of the white parts you see in the pictures are printed in ABS. Some of them are already uploaded to my things collection. The rest will follow soon (also the stickers on the front and right side). If you have feedback for this 'thing' please don't hesitate to comment or write a message to me. Thanks.

description.text:
TriGen is a unique 3D game board where you work your way around the board (clockwise or counterclockwise), attempting to move up each level (when landing exactly on a Green Triangle) as quickly as possible, in an effort to be the first one to reach level 6! Avoid dropping down a level (when landing exactly on a White Triangle). Pull a Dragon card, or Monkey card when landing exactly on a Dragon or Monkey triangle. (I'm still working on these cards).
Dragon cards will boost your position, while Monkey cards will allow you to play havoc on your competing players. The game is designed to be played with two dice, and with 2, 3, 4, 5, or 6 players. I have included three sample game pieces (i.e., the Rat, Dragon, and Monkey). I've upload three exports, in .stl (mono), .wrl (full color), and .x3d (full color). Enjoy! If you like this game please feel free to donate $1.00 to my paypal account ([email protected]) P.S. In the pictures the see through posts are cutouts where players will place the game pieces as they move around the board. P.P.S.S. As a super bonus I've added an archive.zip file which includes exploded files for each level (in all three file formats (i.e., .stl, .wrl, and .x3d). If you want to create the full size model seen in the pictures I've uploaded, you will need to print each component in the proper color, and then assemble all the part to make the completed full color model. I printed this on a MakerBot Replicator 5th generation and set the individual sizes to 200% of original. Additionally, each of the black levels, I cut into three equal pieces and also printed at 200% of the original size. One alibi, the model files uploaded included the placement of holes for the game pieces. The example I printed was completed before I had this amazing brainiac idea! Good luck and enjoy!!! P.S. I hold a provisional patent on this design, so please use accordingly!
I used TinkerCAD, and created six individual triangle layers, outlined with colored triangle which create the game playing surfaces.

These are the final files for making 200 unique wedding favor ornaments so that you can do something similar. It is meant to have each wedding favor have a unique name, similar to a prayer intention, and each guest will receive one unique to them. I didn't want to create all them "manually" using OpenScad so with some amazing hand-holding by Arthur C. Shaw III from this request in G+: https://plus.google.com/u/0/108934380839681630540/posts/1KXvxKhZGi8 mostly he created a command-line python program that will create all 200 without any intervention. Everything is placed in the zip file, including the specialized font that I also created. The main difference between this and intermediate is that this has better font and spacing through trial and error as well as I removed our wedding info on the back so you didn't have to remove that yourself.

First, I took an amazing SVG from images by heatherm: http://imagesbyheatherm.wordpress.com/2011/01/18/filigree-heart-svg-repost-with-updated-file/ and extruded it. I then put a backing on it by copying the svg, erasing the filigree, and then extruding the outline. I sandwiched them together in Tinkercad. I made that object a module in OpenSCAD using an STL to module converter by Riham.
I created a more script-like font (although it is technically monospaced), for use with write.scad (thank you HarlanDMiii for the tool and the troubleshooting) and did a little OpenSCAD "scripting" to have each word display correctly within the heart. Then we packaged that all up into a python script that would create STL's from OpenSCAD's command line function and using the weddinglist.txt file to run through all 200 words while I watched Continuum. I got to the episode where...just kidding, no spoilers but I got through about 4 episodes while it was running. Thank you everyone for your help. This was clearly a mash-up of a lot of different ideas that will hopefully show people the amazing things that can ONLY be done with a 3D printer. Can you imagine making 200 molds?

Push It is a tense game of skill that can be played anywhere. To win, push, flick or judo-chop your pucks so they are closest to the central jack at the end of the round. Sound simple? Well, it is! Find any smooth surface (tables are ideal, and luckily most people have them), whip out your Push It case, and play with whoever is up to the challenge. The game is quick to learn but hard to master. Come up against a Push It maestro and you’ll soon be put in your place (Warning: friendships can suffer as direct result of Push It). Play Push It either mano-a-mano, 3 player, 4 player or our favorite and most strategic version is two teams of two.  
With Push It we want you to unleash your creativity, so there are no long-winded rules or measuring; players have to argue amongst themselves to agree whose puck is closest, or else a ‘Push Off’ tie-break round decides. Only you can tell if that was really ‘cheek lifting’ and not ‘bum shuffling’. It’s all about having your own house rules, playing on different surfaces like car bonnets or pizza trays (tried and tested) and WINNING. So when the pressure is on and you’re going for that extra point (without knocking your opponent’s puck closer), try to remember – it’s just for fun!

Materials:
  • Print 2 off "pinion_ends".
  • Print 1 off "outer_between_pinions".
  • Print 1 off "thumb_wheel".
  • Print 2 off "conduit_bracket_brace_end".
  • Print 1 off "conduit_bracket_brace_join_LHS".
  • Print 1 off "conduit_bracket_brace_join_RHS".
  • Print 4 off "conduit_bracket_brace_slotted"
  • Print 4 off "rack_end".
  • Print 2 off "rack".
  • 2 off 6 x 6 x 40mm timber or nylon key (stiff but machinable material).
  • 6 off M3x20mm machine screws.
  • 6 off M3 nuts.
  • 12 of M3 washers.
  • 6 off 4Gx9mm self tapping screws.
  • 2 off 4Gx16mm self tapping screws.
    • Assembly of gear axle:
  • Insert keys into "pinion_ends"; file to tight fit.
  • Insert "outer_between_pinions" into "thumb_wheel"; roughly half way.
  • Insert "pinion_end" keys into "outer_between_pinions".
  • This will be secured to collars in Instructable assembly.
    • Assembly of brace arms:
  • Secure 1 off "conduit_bracket_brace_slotted" (through the slot) to "conduit_bracket_brace_join_LHS" (on the flat) with a M3x20mm screw, washers and nut.
  • Repeat for the other hole on "conduit_bracket_brace_join_LHS".
  • Repeat #1 & #2 for "conduit_bracket_brace_join_RHS".
